<font color="#FF0000">PLACING BLAME</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb 16 16:31:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Nurse Ratchet has hit the nail right on the head.<br><br>
I never wasted a minute being angry at any who protested the war, rather I always wondered why those she or he has mentioned, MacNamara, Nixon, Johnson, et al, were not held as accountable as the Jane Fondas?<br><br>
MacNamara, the Secretary of Defense who sent men to die for a &quot;mission&quot; he felt in his heart was a mistake!<br><br>
Nixon: I attended a political rally for him in the fall of 1968 at Mt Prospect (ILL) High School. I cheered wildly as he promised to end the war. Slightly more than 4 years later, after thousands more American and millions more Vietnamese lost their lives; he declared that there was &quot;peace with honor&quot;. Nevermind that hundreds of thousands of North Vietnamese Regular troops were not forced to leave South Vietnam. We had abandoned our allies. Nixon had his honor.<br><br>
Johnson decided not to run for reelection because a broad section of Americans had lost patience with his bumbling uncertainty. How long is a citizenry expected to willingly offer up their sons for such a doubtful and ill conceived enterprise? So he QUIT! The Commander In Chief jumped ship! He stood on the shore, watching as those who rode the ship were cast adrift.<br><br>
And people who post to this group actually wonder why young men of draft age weren't enthused about fighting in Vietnam? <br><br>
When I returned from Vietnam in December of 1970, I didn't expect a thing from those who protested. <br><br>
I was to learn a lesson. I was to learn that the ones who, years prior, had given their assent to fighting the war, now didn't want to hear about it. They didn't want to hear about the jungles, the rice paddies, the thirst, the drudgery, the terror, and the death. There was a DENIAL that these conditions, and the men who endured them, ever existed.<br><br>
It is the ultimate in ironies that Vietnam Veterans tell <br>
each other, &quot;Welcome Home&quot;. Think about that one.<br><br>
Did we expect the hippies to have parades for us or would it have been more appropriate for our &quot;supporters&quot; to welcome us home and learn about what we had become?<br><br>
We each had the same choices go or stay home or leave the country or go to jail. My choice was to go. I will live with it and will always be satisfied that it was the right coice for me.<br><br>
But the anger I read on this website is mostly misplaced anger.<br><br>
Point your finger at those who sent you.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


